The paper discusses consensus protocols and their analysis, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses the security aspects of the protocol, which falls under the category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR). The paper proposes a methodology for determining the quorum systems resulting from individual configurations, which falls under the category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the effects of different node configuration policies, which falls under the category of Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI). Lastly, the paper investigates the reported "open-membership" property of FBASs, which falls under the category of Systems and Control (cs.SY).
